Given an array nums of size n, return the majority element.
The majority element is the element that appears more than âŒŠn / 2âŒ‹ times. You may assume that the majority element always exists in the array.

Example 2:
Input: nums = [2,2,1,1,1,2,2]
Output: 2

Solution: 
Boyer-Moore Voting Algorithm used

var majorityElement = function(nums) {
    var maj = 0;     //considering index 0 value could be the majority element
    var count = 1;
    for(i=0; i<nums.length; i++){
        if(nums[i] === nums[maj]){
            count++;
        }
        else
        count--;
        if(count === 0){
            maj = i;  //pick new element for the majority element
            count = 1 //count reset
        }
    }
    return nums[maj]
};


â±ï¸ Time Complexity: O(n)
- The for loop runs once for every element in the array nums
- So, the overall time taken grows linearly with the size of the input â†’ O(n)

ðŸ§  Space Complexity: O(1)
- This algorithm only uses a fixed number of variables (maj, count, i)
- So, the space used stays constant, no matter how large the input â†’ O(1)




[NOTE]

Imagine you're watching a vote battle between numbers.
You start by choosing the first number as your candidate.

For every new number:
: If it's the same as your current candidate, it gets a vote (count++ âœ…)
: If it's different, it's a vote against your candidate (count-- âŒ)
: If the count drops to 0, it means your current candidate got cancelled out. So you pick a new candidate from the current number and reset the count to 1.
: At the end of the array, the candidate left standing is your majority winner! ðŸ†
Also, If we started with count = 0, then on the first iteration (i = 1), we'd immediately risk resetting the candidate (because count === 0 would trigger a new candidate too early) â€” 
which would mess up the Boyer-Moore voting logic.
